Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Penal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the release of the former prime minister, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes in second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for the alleged signing of a deal with Russia disadvantageous to Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The ruling is not yet final, and the court of appeal has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that this was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West doubts have arisen about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Penal Code condemning the former Prime Minister was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
226 votes were required for approval.
