Daily menu of an obese child: no breakfast and dinner sausages
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have problems with overweight, where overweight affects 9% of the school population and obesity affects 5%.
Obese children come mostly from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, according to current research.
It re-demonstrates the importance of the environment where it grows for a healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as reference.
At the table, obese children eat, for example, sausages at least twice as often as children in normal-weight families.
For dinner, more than 19% of the obese had eaten chips the day before the analysis, which is linked to the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence".
In families of overweight children there is no practice of sports, which is applicable to most current families, where only 15% of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and nearly 900 basic education children from all over the Czech Republic participated in the same survey.
It was already the second edition of the program "Obesity is not a coincidence", which supports the General Health Insurance Company and the company Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 children have participated in the project from the 4th to the 8th grade.
A proper diet and plenty of exercise in the family are determining factors, which significantly reduce the number of overweight and even obese children.
“Only half of the children surveyed have responded that they have five meals a day according to the diet: breakfast, lunch, lunch, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet,” one of the survey results found.
No breakfast but with sausage for dinner
Specialists warn that, in healthy development, details are also important, which also count, such as having a fixed time for family breakfast.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of school families eat breakfast at the same time.
In most families, each has breakfast alone.
But the worst thing was to find that in 10% of households, nothing is eaten.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a correct daily diet.
The study shows that families of obese children consume insane chips much more often.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet soft drinks daily (70%).
As a rule, more than 40% of the children surveyed do sports, however, among their parents this result is reduced to less than half, only 15%.
Make your diet
The next phase of the study made it possible for the chosen boys (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15, from the point of view of a healthy diet, are far from ideal."
Among your favorite foods are pasta, meat and sweets
“The popularity of sweet sodas is alarming,” the study’s final report warns.
As the main meal, the palm takes the pasta and follows closely the poultry meat.
Practically, children always reject legumes and the taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Change to Healthy Habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
“In the control group of study participants, who filled out the questionnaire after completing the prevention program ‘Obesity is not a coincidence’, there was in many cases a major shift in favor of the principles of healthy eating,” the study results point out.
It draws attention, for example, to sweet soft drinks, where many children would begin to prefer normal, running water.
Children would also more frequently choose poultry meat and fish for the main meal and restrict the consumption of sweet food and flour derivatives.
