For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet a hundred years have passed since its foundation.
The foundation for this long-standing character was laid by the firm’s first head, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
Already he coined the motto that many of the world’s problems have a solution if people are willing to think.
Its motto "Think!" became its hallmark, around which the life of the future giant will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the foundation of a carefully raised corporate culture.
“For us, IBM involves long-term thinking, a continuous move toward the future.
IBM has survived and prospered for a hundred years for that reason, because it remained true to its basic principles, but without fear of changes around.
That has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We look forward to further prospering in our second century,” said current company director Samuel J. Palmisano during his anniversary.
A sophisticated system
Watson, as early as the 1930s, cared about caring for his employees as the Ba<0xC5><0xA5>a businessman in the Czech Republic (IBM employees were among the first American workers to enjoy paid vacation, insurance, elegant uniforms and a sophisticated remuneration system that rewarded the best inventors and sellers.
The same long-term sophistication is maintained by IBM in the customer relationship.
From the beginning, the company knew how to discover talent (being one of the first companies in the world to end any type of discrimination, it could choose without problems).
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy is IBM’s current plan, by which Palmisano will be replaced next year by a woman: Virginia Rometty.
She has been working at IBM for thirty years, where she has been Head of Sales, Marketing and Strategy.
In recent years IBM has participated in the so-called virtual meetings, online brainstorming, from which countless future strategies and innovations emerge.
It is not surprising that there are plenty of ideas, as almost half a million people work at the firm.
An institution with a good reputation
The fixed position in the business provides the company with a strong internal and external image.
“From the beginning, IBM maintained a concept of an institution rather than a technology company,” says Harvard Business School economist and author of the book on IBM Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company trying to solve business problems for technology users,” said George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, there is a difference between entering the business and directly creating a business.
IBM - or the "Great Green" - as it is known in the U.S. familiarly because of its logo, has become in the last hundred years one of the largest companies in the world.
It is arguably the most versatile technology company (develops both equipment and programs, infrastructures and web hosting services within a wide range of services, ranging from servers to nanotechnology).
It holds the highest number of patents of all U.S. tech companies and five of its employees have received the Nobel Prize.
Among his inventions are the ATM, payment cards, financial swaps, bar codes and floppy disks.
IBM will bill $220 billion this year. This year it has become the second tech firm by market capitalization (the first is Apple), when it first overtook Microsoft in 1996.
Looking into the future
Not all products and innovations just satisfy the taste of customers and the moment (IBM did not bet on its own operating system, OS/2, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers).
“If your business is based on moving forward, you can’t anchor yourself emotionally in the past,” said Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its bases on other platforms (and also, if they don’t work, abandons them).
And that differentiates it from the competition, Microsoft, which basically stays and always falls exclusively with Windows.
Technology of the future
In terms of sales, IBM is mainly engaged in services, of which approximately one-fifth are programs and one-fifth are computers.
However, even in 1990, teams accounted for more than half of the share of suppliers.
As of the year 2000, IBM has sold low-performing assets worth a total of $15 billion, and over the same period has invested $58 billion in the purchase of future-oriented technology.
Investments have continued since 2008, when the modern global financial crisis first emerged.
IBM operates on the premises of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who during the great economic crisis of 29 increased investment.
It seems that so far the IBM company has managed to overcome the crisis.
The value of IBM shares since the beginning of 2008 has grown stratospherically to 120%, the company’s net profit has not stopped increasing.
IBM’s currency is to change everything except its value.
One can therefore expect that when the next crisis comes, this flexible giant will endure.
IBM History: From the Cheese Cutter to Spaceflight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, its original name being Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 – originally it was a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation that led to the birth of IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He possessed inventions such as the famous "signing clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint hired the head of a competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The new leader eclipsed IBM’s founder (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are built).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began producing and selling all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years Watson led the company, turnover doubled by $9 million and the company’s massive continental expansion began.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after almost forty years in the chair of the boss, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began work on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights into space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
In 1964, IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "peces", which introduced the standard of computers of that time, came to the market under the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which in turn acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began offering comprehensive advice and high value-added services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept, meaning “a smarter planet.”
Its aim is to make a more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned and circumstances have not been improved, for example in terms of transport and city administration.
For the commerce sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 he opened a branch in Czechoslovakia, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague. Also here is a world-famous research team that works with voice recognition.
