How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989 there were in Czechoslovakia only five authorized state travel agencies: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time mostly sold trips only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists were therefore on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea), Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, after the Yugoslav regime leaned westward and travel of Czech tourists was then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (that is, also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies at the time also offered trips to the West, but one had to queue up with a sleeping bag and spend the night like this, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" which was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way Czechs travel has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, that to the currently favourite destination, Croatia, until 1989 it was not possible to travel freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia at that time.
In the early 1990s, visa-free travel to neighbouring Western European states was imposed, prompting a huge surge of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, were not fed up with the excursions to the west, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in parks in tents, since our income at the time did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical characteristic of the Czechs of that time was to take food (canned, sausages, etc.) with them to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so that our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was increasing and with it also average wages, which around 1997 caused an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in demand for travel agencies began, from 1997 onwards, to regularly prepare travel using charter flight connections, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts on passenger volume.
By the late 1990s, Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the US, which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened as early as 2000, when it was organized, thanks to enormous demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists depart every year to distant and warm countries. This winter will already fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this epoch, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, they have spent more than 15,000 Czech crowns per capita on foreign trips, including on-site expenses.
