7 Lessons From Steve Jobs’ Missing Interview, Shown In A Theater This Week
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the tech genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered Jobs interview that has been dusted off as a preview of a series of special projections in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the business processes and workflows of the products.
He was certainly a designer, dreamer and self-recognized hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a yonki of flowcharts – a man who believed that many executives suffered “a disease consisting of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the job... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
By that time, it had barely been 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively on his new computer company NeXT, waiting for popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely’s interview was used on Nerds, he said the interview’s originals disappeared during their transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full copy was discovered on VHS in the director's garage.
This slightly re-edited footage is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute Missing Interview, which hits Landmark theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his tech philosophies and trading strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers – from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking accuracy.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient due to Cringely’s questions, pushing him to go faster toward the most important themes or arguments.
Filmed before the Pixar era, the iPod or the iPhone, there’s something strangely prophetic about The Missing Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision for the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous assessments of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Missing Interview:
About how you learned to run a business:
“Over the years in the business, I’d always ask, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers they give you invariably are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
No one knows why he does what he does, in business nobody thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs details his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting.
Bewildered by the way costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was done with a good eye, and then adjusted with a "variable" - he developed an automated factory that ensured they could determine business costs in detail.
The joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" he built himself with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been widely written about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world a half-dozen times and screaming through the public phone and going back a minute later to the public phone from the next door,” Jobs says with a laugh.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both, we didn’t know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing – it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak with the Pope, while making his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the Pope himself was woken up to answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling over the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made him a call.
Shortly after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs landed a summer part-time job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had ever seen at that age and it formed my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.”
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste time on that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Soon in his career, as he devoted himself to selling a handful of motherboards, he was asked by a client if he could assemble the whole equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments ... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got fed up and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On the big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple’s renaissance, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble in his vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say that you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make photocopiers and printers better, and what?"
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company is no longer successful.
The sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is this kind of people who end up running the companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the forum for decision-making.
The product genius that led to that monopoly position is rotting because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs. bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the '90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as artistic expression:
“There’s a huge amount of work going on between a great idea and a great product...as the great idea evolves, changes and grows.”
A lot is learned about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make – some things you can’t make electrons do, glass does, robots do, factories do.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end, it all comes down to taste – it comes down to trying to expose yourself to the best that a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you’re doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have never been ashamed of stealing great ideas.
What partly made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who casually were the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren’t for computer science, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas dine with health care law rivals as court accepts case
On the day the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to examine the politically controversial question of whether they would accept President Obama’s health care law challenge, two of his magistrates, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were hosted at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will lay the case before the high court.
The occasion was last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to thoroughly study the petitions for review.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging total health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a battle cry for conservative activists across the country.
