Days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a planned pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico -- enraged unions while appeasing environmentalists -- the company looking to build the pipeline says it is willing to redirect the project to reroute it.
TransCanada said Monday night it will move the planned pipeline out of the ecologically sensitive Sandhills area in Nebraska, and is confident the project will win approval.
The company announced the decision at the Nebraska Capitol press conference.
TransCanada’s director, Alex Pourbax, says the company maintains its confidence that over time the pipeline will be approved, although it is true that with a different route.
This comes after the State Department’s announcement last week that it would delay the decision for a federal permit for the project until potential new routes to avoid the Nebraska Sandhills areas and the Ogallala Aquifer, a vast supply of groundwater, are studied.
“This is a real path to progress,” Rep. Lee Terry, a Nebraska Republican, told Fox News.
The new environmental review ordered by the State Department may set aside any decision until 2013 after next year’s elections, although officials denied the policy was involved in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as the State Department’s request, and expressed his full support for them.
The 1,700-kilometre pipeline would extend from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would take 700,000 barrels a day from the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
To do this, it would be necessary to cross six states.
It is hated by environmentalists, but loved by working groups, who have bet on the estimate of 20,000 jobs linked to the pipeline.
But Nebraska lawmakers opposed to the plan are weighing legislation to force a move away from the Sandhills region and the Ogallala aquifer, the largest source of drinking water and irrigation.
The State Department’s current environmental impact study found that the project only raised limited adverse environmental impacts, but the energy industry source said the department’s inspector general has ordered an independent test of the review process, focusing on two issues.
One is whether the lobbyist hired by TransCanada, Paul Elliot, who was Hillary Clinton’s campaign adviser in 2008, represents a conflict of interest for the program.
The other is whether a firm that was hired to run the original studio was an inappropriate choice because it was linked to TransCanada.
