Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the plane crash where the Secretary of the Governorate, Francisco Blake, and seven others lost their lives
The Ministry of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which the Secretary of the Governorate, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven others lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter was directly impacted on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"The elements that appear to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with trees 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
It also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that the investigations carried out in the impact zone did not report the appearance of parts on the ground.
“In a search it is reported that there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was presented structurally.
“The design of the helicopter was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to transport passengers.
The terrain has a seven-degree slope at 30 degrees of inclination.
For the time being, the secretary said that it is a priority to have the results before possible; however, the investigation can last several months, it could even reach a year.
Gilberto Lopez Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was operating at cruising speed and that this happened in a soft ascending terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations the flight was carried out under the visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the ground.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM located suitable conditions for take-off, as the aircraft advanced towards the area bordering the DF and the State of Mexico presented layers of cloudiness at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloudy conditions the crew sought an area of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The impact coordinates and the last record of the radar aircraft coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a reduced zone:
The information available so far allows us to assume that the impact occurred on a straight and sideways trajectory.
The scattering pattern of the aircraft debris allows us to assume that the helicopter was impacted on the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the accident, there is still no evidence of an explosion or fire in the wreckage of the ship.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the fieldwork, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above average sea level, the terrain has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was foreseeably disarticulated along said path.
The information provides evidence that appears to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After the thorough search in a wider area than the cordoned site, around the crash, no scattered pieces of the aircraft have been found, which strengthens the presumption that the impact was presented under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security Leads Research to Discover the Obesity Gene in Children and Youth; Supported by IPN Specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called 'Genetics of childhood obesity and adolescence' protocol, which will allow markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialty Hospital of the National Medical Center XXI Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the population whether or not entitled to participate, to go to the sports units participating in the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests for minors are carried out, every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México West) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is achieved, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the appearance of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day is celebrated on November 14, he said the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific questionnaires on food.
They will also be asked about physical activity and hereditary family history of diseases, with the purpose of avoiding risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
On Saturdays, anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure measurement, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetics are applied to all participants (it is sought to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz Lopez pointed out that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
"The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and in the case of girls, of 47 percent; in terms of overweight there was also a dramatic rise," said the IMSS specialist.
He said the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country’s population differs from others because of its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European and five percent African heritage and this condition is reflected in genes that are associated with diabetes and excess weight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translate into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows to detect if they have some degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (cantoses) on the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors give it in writing to the parents, who are explained each of the measurements and lifestyle changes that must be made to prevent disease.
