It is also due to the high caloric intake, that is, the increased consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, burger, etc.) with high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid bumps
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions.
If the signs sent by the pavement were taken care of, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 potholes each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of a pavement could even be reduced by amount, or asphalts is the right,
In his lecture A technological opinion of the potholes, issued in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he revealed that the laboratory in charge develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of petroleum, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that on the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but is modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The CF researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which is composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve the asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt binder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that make up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
By moving vehicles and generating efforts, it allows forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
Over the asphalt binder, abounded, is placed a last layer called rolling binder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it should have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the efforts, the treadmill also requires having the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt binder.
When the ground gets wet, the water diffuses inside the binder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a bump, he said, the first to wear out is the rolling film and only then is the asphalt folder affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be taken care of at the first signals with appropriate maintenance programs.
The also member of the National System of Investigators explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each of the pavement layers must always be in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is complied with, to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to be done to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and allow to repair potholes easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
