The Nord Stream, new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia via the Baltic Sea bottom, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
On Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, in the opening of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his counterpart from the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have together turned the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western Europe network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will reach Western Europe each year through a first had of 1,224 km connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline is expected to be completed by the end of 2012 to supply a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this enormous work presents an air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding land travel by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has obtained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the energy Europe, given that the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy, gas-consuming Western countries with increasingly limited reserves.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically,” Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon said at the opening of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which major gas contracts are as political as they are economic.
All of this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the Gazprom executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against ship anchors.
It rests on the sea floor, at an average of 200 m depth.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to withdraw or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to implement measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in its entire length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden’s waters, but project leaders renounced it when they saw that the Swedes were not too willing to allow a Russian state company to settle permanently in the sea off their shores.
"In the event of a breakdown, we will interrupt the passage of the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, as they have foreseen joints that are predicted to have a leak every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, which performs external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is ensured simply by the pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is especially favorable.
Gazprom then leased to that company, for a renewable period of twenty-five years, all gas transport capacities.
“Gazprom will pay you for the full capacity, regardless of how much gas is actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been carried out in 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and in 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the project is expected to reach €7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are certain that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of expenses.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet gate.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
As of Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as if aged by time.
However, Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook of design, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was in charge of launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton used, among other things, to cover the stools.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted an old and forgotten object to today's taste, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first few years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed, is far away.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer’s profile, as the notebook appeals to both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which had twelve employees at the beginning, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the center of the cities, and has been able to impose his identity.
“We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard covers, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, diaries, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19 per cent, compared to 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Discouraging?
"No," says <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the last 15 years is considerable.
At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a lot to be done."
It should be noted that disabled unemployed people continue to face numerous barriers to accessing employment.
They usually have an older age: 37% are over 50 years old (an average of 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared with an average of 38%.
That is, there are numerous issues that make it especially difficult to return to the world of work and that "are the crux of the problem", says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; people’s mentality advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité association noted that the directors surveyed have “a low level of knowledge about disabilities,” with “overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, physically or intellectually impaired.”
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the target of hiring 6% disabled workers, a target that was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest figures available, which date from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"We now reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body in charge of collecting contributions from companies that do not respect this law.
The proof: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects real awareness, particularly among large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees, compared to 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 employees.
